Number = {{2}},
Pages = {{82-96}},
Abstract = {{Deforestation principally to establish cattle pastures has created large
   expanses of land dominated by exotic grass prior to the establishment of
   the Cerro Blanco Protected Forest in Ecuador. A dry forest restoration
   program was carried out from 2008 to 2017. Tree planting sites were
   cleared in parallel lines through abandoned pasture and secondary
   vegetation using manual labor. Native tree species were produced in a
   nursery on site and used in yearly plantings during the rainy season. A
   total of 637 hectares were planted at an average stocking density of
   1,000 trees per hectare. Growth data was collected from trees planted in
   nine sites from 2008 to 2017. Mortality rates were determined from a
   sample of 400 trees of twenty-two species. Survival of all species was
   greater than 50\%. Ten species had survival rates greater than 90\%.
   Vitex gigantea, with high survival rates, also had significantly greater
   growth rates than the other species (p < 0.0001) and showed the greatest
   yearly accumulation of total carbon (2.07 Kg C yr(-1) stem(-1)). Other
