Abstract = {{An 8-ha, extremely rich fen, surrounded by saline wet meadows, occurs on
   the western edge of mixed-grass prairie in the northwestern Great
   Plains, 47 km east of the Montana Rocky Mountain Front. The site occurs
   on an outwash plain near the junction of Pleistocene-age continental and
   mountain glaciers and on the western edge of former glacial Cut Bank
   Lake. Five wetland plant communities are described from this site. A
   total of 93 vascular plant and 65 diatom species have been found. Twelve
   diatom taxa could not be identified with available floras and one has
   been confirmed as new to science. Both diatoms and vascular plants
   indicate a locally disjunct, post-glacial assemblage similar to those
   found in boreal and mountainous habitats, adapted to alkaline waters.
   Saline-influenced, extremely rich fens are a rare sub-type of peatland
   in the northern Great Plains, and contain high diatom and vascular plant
   species richness as well as rare taxa.}},
