Abstract = {{Active revegetation is an essential component of biodiversity
   conservation for fragmented ecosystems and the species that depend on
   them. However, key knowledge gaps exist around the most cost-effective
   revegetation strategies to employ in different contexts. This article
   reports on a revegetation trial undertaken in the Capertee Valley of New
   South Wales, Australia, to assist the conservation of the critically
   endangered bird, the Regent Honeyeater (Anthochaera phrygia). Seven
   treatments were compared to assess their cost-effectiveness for
   enhancing plant survival at a floodplain site with a history of grazing
   on introduced pastures. While overall survival rates were low,
   treatments involving tree guards had higher survival rates and were more
   cost-effective than treatments without guards. Weed growth, animal
   activity and water stress all appeared to play a role in the low
   survival rates at this site, with enhanced weed control emerging as a
   priority for future trials at similar sites.}},
