   and ecosystem function on the grasslands of Inner Mongolia, China}},
Journal = {{SCIENTIFIC REPORTS}},
Year = {{2017}},
Volume = {{7}},
Month = {{FEB 28}},
Abstract = {{Grasslands worldwide are suffering from overgrazing, which greatly
   alters plant community structure and ecosystem functioning. However, the
   general effects of grazing on community structure and ecosystem function
   at spatial and temporal scales has rarely been examined synchronously in
   the same grassland. Here, during 2011-2013, we investigated community
   structure (cover, height, and species richness) and aboveground biomass
   (AGB) using 250 paired field sites (grazed vs. fenced) across three
   vegetation types (meadow, typical, and desert steppes) on the Inner
   Mongolian Plateau. Grazing, vegetation type, and year all had
   significant effects on cover, height, species richness, and AGB,
