Journal = {{CRUSTACEANA}},
Year = {{2017}},
Volume = {{90}},
Number = {{11-12}},
Pages = {{1319-1335}},
Abstract = {{Temporal variability in species composition and abundance may enhance
   coexistence in ecological communities, especially when subjected to
   strong seasonal patterns. Species distribution through time may be
   related to many factors, such as changes in the structure and
   functioning of preferred habitats, variations in ecological interactions
   or asynchronous patterns in species life cycles. Here, data from a
   one-year survey of amphipod assemblages from a nearly undisturbed
   Posidonia oceanica meadow are used to investigate the seasonal patterns
   in species abundance and identity. Our results highlight the presence of
   a core group of species inhabiting the meadow throughout the year,
   although an in depth analysis reveals three differentiated seasonal
   assemblages corresponding to autumn, winter, and a warm season
   clustering of both spring and summer. The observed patterns suggest the
   interplay between different mechanisms drives the coexistence of
   amphipods over the whole year, including niche partitioning, predation
   pressure, and variations in life history traits.}},
