Abstract = {{Maintenance of biodiversity in tropical agrarian landscapes is
   challenging in the face of anthropomorphic simplification of habitats.
   As part of an experiment testing influences of planting treatment on
   tree recruitment in southern Mexico, counts of bird species were made
   over 10 years in twenty-four 30x30-m fenced plots in over-grazed
   pasture. Plots were planted with native tree species or left as
   unplanted controls in 2006. Annual censuses of birds in the plots from
   2007-2016 indicated statistically significant increases in the number of
   fruit-eating species and individuals as vegetation matured, but
   increases in non-frugivorous species and individuals over the decade
   were not significant. Among four species of planted animal-dispersed
   trees that bore fruit during this time, Cecropia obtusifolia
   consistently produced substantial crops after 2009. In 2015, all 53
   planted or passively recruited female trees of mature size of this
   species bore fruit. The summed body masses of fruit-eating birds in each
   of 24 plots were significantly correlated with rank order of available
   fruit per plot. Differential use of habitat patches in an agrarian
   landscape suggested substantial value to frugivores, but less to
   non-frugivorous birds than expected.}},
